25|$|Semiotics {{operates}} {{under the}} theory that an image can only be understood from the viewer’s perspective. The artist is supplanted by the viewer as the purveyor of meaning, even {{to the extent that}} an interpretation is still valid regardless of whether the creator had intended it. Rosalind Krauss espoused this concept <b>in</b> <b>her</b> <b>essay</b> “In the Name of Picasso.” She denounced the artist’s monopoly on meaning and insisted that meaning can only be derived after the work has been removed from its historical and social context. Mieke Bal argued similarly that meaning does not even exist until the image is observed by the viewer. It is only after acknowledging this that meaning can become opened up to other possibilities such as feminism or psychoanalysis.|$|E
